HOUSE BILL No. 1102
A BILL FOR AN ACT to amend the Indiana Code concerning
education.
Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the State of Indiana:
1 SECTION 1. IC 20-35-15 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
2 AS A NEW CHAPTER TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
3 JULY 1, 2026]:
4 Chapter 15. Access to Services by Licensed or Board Certified
5 Behavior Analysts
6 Sec. 1. This chapter applies to a public school, including a
7 charter school.
8 Sec. 2. As used in this chapter, "licensed or board certified
9 behavior analyst" means a behavior analyst with credentialing as
10 a licensed or board certified:
11 (1) behavior analyst doctoral; or
12 (2) behavior analyst.
13 Sec. 3. (a) This section applies to a student to whom the
14 following applies:
15 (1) The student:
16 (A) is receiving applied behavioral analysis therapy
17 services from a licensed or board certified behavior
HB 1102—LS 6549/DI 110

2
1 analyst; and
2 (B) has recently enrolled in a public school.
3 (2) The provision of applied behavioral analysis therapy
4 services are included as part of the student's:
5 (A) individualized education program; or
6 (B) plan developed under Section 504 of the federal
7 Rehabilitation Act of 1973, 29 U.S.C. 794.
8 (b) Upon request by the parent of the student or the student, if
9 the student is an adult or emancipated minor, a public school shall
10 do the following:
11 (1) Consult with a licensed or board certified behavior analyst
12 described in subsection (a)(1)(A) regarding the provision of
13 applied behavioral analysis therapy services for the student.
14 (2) Allow:
15 (A) the licensed or board certified behavior analyst
16 described in subdivision (1); and
17 (B) as applicable, a certified registered behavior technician
18 who works with the analyst described in clause (A);
19 to provide behavioral analysis therapy services that are
20 within the scope of the analyst's or technician's scope of
21 practice as established by the Behavior Analyst Certification
22 Board to the student at the public school for not less than
23 thirty (30) days and, unless otherwise recommended by the
24 licensed or board certified behavior analyst, not more than
25 ninety (90) days after the date the student begins attending the
26 public school.
27 (c) The presence or participation of a licensed or board certified
28 behavior analyst under this section is not a designation of a service
29 provider for purposes of 511 IAC 7 or the federal Individual with
30 Disabilities Education Act (IDEA).
31 (d) An individualized education program is not required to
32 identify an individual licensed or board certified behavior analyst
33 by name.
34 (e) Nothing in this section may be construed to restrict or limit
35 a public school from allowing an analyst or technician described in
36 subsection (b)(2) to provide behavioral analysis therapy services to
37 a student beyond the ninety (90) day period described in subsection
38 (b)(2).
39 Sec. 4. (a) Before an analyst or technician described in section
40 3(b) of this chapter provides behavioral analysis therapy services
41 in a public school under this chapter, the public school shall do the
42 following:
HB 1102—LS 6549/DI 110

3
1 (1) Unless the public school receives results under subdivision
2 (2), conduct an expanded criminal history check and
3 expanded child protection index check as described in
4 IC 20-26-5-10 of the analyst or technician.
5 (2) Accept the results of an expanded criminal history check
6 and expanded child protection index check that was
7 conducted within the immediately preceding five (5) years if
8 the results are provided to the public school by the analyst or
9 technician.
10 (b) An analyst or technician described in section 3(b) of this
11 chapter is responsible for all costs associated with obtaining the
12 expanded criminal history check and expanded child protection
13 index check unless the public school agrees to pay the costs.
14 Sec. 5. A public school may not allow an analyst or technician
15 described in section 3(b) of this chapter to provide applied
16 behavioral analysis therapy services under this chapter if:
17 (1) the analyst or technician has been convicted of an offense
18 listed in IC 20-28-5-8(c) or described in IC 20-28-5-8(d); and
19 (2) the conviction has not been reversed, vacated, or set aside
20 on appeal.
21 Sec. 6. A school corporation, a public school, and school
22 personnel are immune from civil liability for any actions taken in
23 good faith to comply with this chapter. The civil immunity under
24 this section does not apply to an act or omission that constitutes
25 gross negligence or willful, wanton, or intentional misconduct.
26 Sec. 7. Not later than September 1, 2026, the department shall
27 prepare and provide to public schools information and guidance to
28 assist public schools in implementing this chapter.
29 Sec. 8. Applied behavioral analysis therapy services delivered by
30 a licensed or board certified behavior analyst or registered
31 behavior technician under this chapter retain their
32 characterization as clinical or therapeutic services for purposes of
33 insurance or third party reimbursement.
34 Sec. 9. Nothing in this chapter shall be construed to require a
35 public school to employ, contract with, or pay a licensed or board
36 certified behavior analyst or registered behavior technician who
37 provides applied behavioral analysis therapy services under this
38 chapter. The cost of services delivered by an outside licensed or
39 board certified behavior analyst or registered behavior technician
40 remains the responsibility of the parent or the parent's insurer
41 unless the public school voluntarily agrees to pay.
